resources.string:
	#include<stdio.h>
	void main(){
		float b=5.89;
		printf("%d",(int)b);
		} 
What you seen in the above program is called type casting. Here b an floating point or a decimal value has been converted/printed as an integer values by the use of type cast or using it as an integer by simply adding (int) before it. It can be done vice versa or in other words you can print an int a=10; as 10.0000 using type casting to float i.e. '(float)a'; ;
